	<td width="1%">&nbsp;</td>
	<td width="98%">

		<table width="100%">
		<tr>
			<td>
				<p>
					<font face="verdana" size="3"><b>    Enchanter's Advice</b></font>
					<br>
					<font face="verdana" size="2">
					<b><A href="mailto:JAS0978@earthlink.net">Jeff Sinclair/Zalion</a> | 
		            4/14/1999 2:29:22 PM</b></font></p>
		         <a href="guides.asp">
		         <font face="verdana" size="2">Return to guide listing.</font></a>
					
					<p>
					<font face="verdana" size="2">Enchanters are still considered by many to be a fairly weak class.  That's fine.  It means that enchanters have to uphold certain standards if they're ever going to get enough respect to join a party.  It also means that we are a rare commodity, and the more powerful we get, the more sought out we will become when our unique abilities are needed.<BR>
<BR>
Why?<BR>
<BR>
If you want to become an enchanter, the first question you have to ask yourself is - why?  You will not be a tank.  You will not be a powerful direct damage caster.  You will not be able to heal outside of learning to bind wounds.  Initially, your 'pets' will be of questionable help.  If any of these things are important to you, then don't become an enchanter.<BR>
However, if you want to be able to cast dynamic utility spells with uses so broad they have not been fully explored, then the enchanter is an ideal class.  Most people would be surprised to find out that my own progression as an enchanter has been 97% soloist from levels one through eight.  This is a hard road, but it honestly did not take any longer than any other class' progression.  Hunting and fighting as an enchanter is not an obvious path.  Creativity will be the key to survival and effectiveness.  If you're not willing or able to be creative with what you have been given, start another type of spell caster.<BR>
After seeing the skilled enchanter in action, parties won't overlook you as a member of their group because they think you are weak.  They just won't think you need any help.  Social skills are very important to an enchanter.  The hurdles of a perceived weakness followed by a perceived self-reliance will mean that you will have to be outgoing and helpful.  Although I did not party much, I most likely would have benefited from partying a great deal.  When I did party, I was surprised to find that rather than being treated like a second-class citizen, response to my character was somewhat closer to awe.  Need proof?<BR>
<BR>
Parable of an Enchanter<BR>
<BR>
Zalion started having a hard time fighting in his adopted city of Freeport right around level six.  Every potential foe was either green or deadly.  Using Minor Illusion to pick and choose his fight was no longer a viable option because any fight he picked would kill him or be of no benefit.  It was time to group.<BR>
Zalion had heard of the opinions other adventurers had of his class, and it was with some trepidation that he sat at the edge of the Desert of Ro and waited.  He decided he had to prove his usefulness.  After taking a few jackals out, safely hidden from other more dangerous monsters disguised as a palm tree, Zalion started to draw stares.<BR>
Taking advantage of the attention, Zalion began to cast strengthening and protective spells on people when fights got too close to call.  He started watching people's backs and casting invisibility on those brave souls who decided to plop down and meditate when the deadly spiders and scarabs could come over the hill at any moment.<BR>
Finally, an invitation came.  The party leader asked Zalion if he could heal.  No, he answered, and there was a long pause.  We really need a healer, the leader told him.  Zalion had a twinkle in his eye, as if it could be seen from behind his illusion.  With luck, and my spells, you won't need to heal as much, he finally replied.  Use me correctly, Zalion boasted, and I'm as useful as any other class.<BR>
The boasting became prophetic as Zalion became the party's bait.  Walking up to cutthroat camps just close enough to avoid an attack and using minor illusion and invisibility if it got too risky, Zalion cast lull on the group of monsters assembled.  Then, the target, the un-lulled creature, would get the dubious honor of being targeted by a Tashan enchantment designed to lower the creatures magic resistance.  What's next?  Run, Zalion, run!  It was time for the tanks to step in, with color flux and suffocating sphere to help them out.<BR>
So it went until disaster struck.  The lulls either did not take effect or didn't last very long.  A horde of creatures descended on the party and everyone started taking hits.  Zalion realized that everyone would soon be dead.  Nothing could change that fact.  He didn't think like a fighter, a healer or even a spell slinger.  Zalion thought about what would be best for the party.  Back off, he thought, stop attacking and get out of the fight.  Zalion moved away several steps and took a chance by casting minor illusion, hoping the cutthroats would not remember him.  He looked around.  Everyone was dead, and he was still alive.<BR>
When the group started talking to each other again from their various home points, the immediate concern was where their bodies were located and how they would get them back.  That was when they discovered Zalion's fate.  I'm still in the desert, he told them, right next to your bodies.  I can give you a /loc and protect you while you recover your items.  And if your corpse's coordinates aren't enough, just look for the large spinning totem in the middle of the desert.  Zalion's party was grateful, and learned the subtleties of the art of enchantment.<BR>
Even in failure, an enchanter can find success. <BR>
<BR>
Making the Enchanter<BR>
<BR>
Erudite, High Elf, Gnome, Dark Elf or Human -- the question of race for an enchanter is strictly a matter of taste.  Intelligence and Charisma are the prime statistics for an enchanter.  Humans and Erudites will have to wait for the Level 12 spell Serpent Sight for the best night vision.  Most important is that the race you select is a race you enjoy playing.  Dark Elves will have the hardest time travelling abroad and will be the target of many good-aligned NPCs.  However, a few enchanter spells are rarely found outside of Neriak, the city of the Dark Elves, and it is hard to get inside the city as any other enchanter race without clever, careful use of illusion-type spells and perhaps some assistance from a Dark Elf.  Dark Elves who role play well and worship the evil gods will not necessarily want to help out a High Elf or Gnome, if they are willing to help anyone at all.<BR>
High intelligence will guarantee smooth skill development and is crucial for the types of spells we cast.  Charisma is a hotly debated statistic.  It affects faction and NPC merchant prices.  Most people believe that this is all there is to charisma.  I tend to believe that certain mind-altering enchanter spells are also affected by enchantment.  Illusion spells, charm and other abilities seem to be more or less successful depending on the caster's charisma, but so far that is merely my observation.  As such, keep in mind that while high elves and humans have good charisma, dark elves are somewhat lacking in this statistic.<BR>
The bulk of the thirty bonus points you will receive are generally allocated to intelligence.  It is advisable to devote some of your bonus points to stamina, for better health points and to wisdom to cut down on spell failure.  Agility will help prevent you from getting interrupted while casting in combat.<BR>
<BR>
Now What?<BR>
<BR>
When you enter the world you will have in your possession a dagger, a book, guild initiation scroll (for your class) and two spell scrolls, plus food and water.  Ready the dagger by moving it over the picture of your character, read the initiation scroll, find a comfortable spot to scribe and memorize your spells.  Now find your enchanter's guild.  Class guilds are like schools where you spend training points, buy spells and equipment and get some quests.  The person mentioned in your scroll is the one you want.  Find him/her, give the scroll to him by holding over him and then you'll receive your guild robe/tunic and the opportunity to train for the first time.  <BR>
It is commonly held that most of your training should go into piercing for this initial visit.   Once you can afford a two-handed blunt, you may want to seriously consider changing weapons.  Two-hand blunts do considerably more damage.  This is important in the first dozen or so levels, although older enchanters will rarely do much good with a weapon against the more powerful monsters in the lands.<BR>
Buy new spells often and practice using them in as many ways you can think up.  Other than clothing, food (I recommend fishing), water and one good weapon, all your money will be spent on spells, and you can never have too many.<BR>
<BR>
When You Hunt<BR>
<BR>
Stay close to the city gates, guards or a zone border when you are young.   While I did manage to make it through the first six levels without an animation spell, after I checked out Pendril's Animation (long after it could do me any good because animation spells don't get better as you level) I realized that it could have helped considerably in the beginning.  The tiny daggers you need to buy for a spell component are expensive, however (if only you could find them on tiny monsters&#8230;.)  If you can, get in a group close to your 'age'.  While this won't necessarily help your experience much more than soloing, hunting will seem to go faster and it will be a lot safer.  Never pass by an opportunity to group.  For enchanters, the opportunity to strut our stuff is still too rare.<BR>
I have noticed that most enchanters seem to fight in an almost formulaic manner.  Cast this spell, then that spell, whack it a few times, cast this, then do this.  I have been able to solo and even group so well because I rely on what is going on around me, improvisation, and how the fight goes.  It is fine to have an advance strategy, but an enchanter can't survive as long as a robot.  You could follow a formula for fighting the same creature ten times in a row and it will turn out different each time.  The first time the spell your plan hinges on is resisted you'll be running for a guard, yelling &quot;Train&quot; and leading a whole mess of badness back to the new players.<BR>
Consider, or 'con', everything!  An orc centurion can be anywhere from green to red for a sixth level enchanter.  Don't rely on a creature of the same name being the same difficulty every time.  You'll be rudely awakened to the fact that monsters are strong or weak in much the same way characters are strong or weak.  You'll also be dead.<BR>
<BR>
Spell Book<BR>
<BR>
At this point I would like to mention that I usually get bored with a character very quickly.  Never before have I played a class that holds my interest so well, and continues to surprise me.  I often get no further than level 10 before I'm trying something new.  I don't expect that to happen here.  One good reason for this is the enchanter's spell list.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                            <BR>
There are no huge fireball (yawn!) or magic-missile type spells.  There are no amazing instant resolution spells that allow for a quick kill or a quick fix.  The spell list of an enchanter is a list of possibilities, of unquantified potentials.  It is said that the enchanter excels at screwing around with other's minds, so use your own mind with some flexibility.  This is the thinking man's spell caster.  <BR>
For combat, damage over time is the prevailing theme of the enchanter's offensive spells.  Suffocating Sphere, Choke, Shallow Breath and Suffocate are the offensive spells most familiar to an enchanter.  Shallow Breath does five damage initially, Suffocating Sphere does 10 damage to start, and so forth.  The continuous damage depends on the level of the spell caster and comes every four seconds.  With Suffocating Sphere, the creature's strength and agility are also lowered by five.<BR>
A few direct damage spells come into the mix around level eight, such as Chaotic Feedback, but with a high mana cost.  In general, an enchanter's strength in combat will come from the ability to stun, root, bind, blind, spin, charm, mesmerize, debuff (weaken) and confuse his foes with a variety of spells.  That is just another reason why enchanters must be thoughtful and creative.  It rarely does any good just to hurl damage spells at a creature if you belong to this class.  You must constantly invent and reinvent tactics.  As stated above, certain enchanters follow a set routine, but if they can't be flexible and see that the routine is not working from time to time, they will be dead enchanters.<BR>
Buffing spells are those spells that improve your own (self-cast) and/or another's abilities.  Always keep yourself buffed if hunting alone with haze, strength, etc.  Try to keep your group buffed if mana allows if you are hunting with others.  Keep in mind that if you buff everyone and run out of mana, your party is going to miss your spells when they are truly needed.  You may need to economize and buff only those in the front lines.<BR>
Utility spells are a great strength in enchantment.  They are each unique and have a variety of uses so I will list several of them here, alone or in categories:<BR>
Minor Illusion: A very useful spell.  Use it to meditate, hunt in dangerous areas (using a ranged attack or spell to bring the creature to you), recover your body without getting whacked on the head while picking things up, etc, but please do not abuse this spell!  If you're bored, you can even fish under minor illusion.  Using this spell was very humorous when I first picked it up.  People are more used to seeing enchanters under this spell's effects now, however.  Turning into the outer gates of Felwithe and spinning while people are trying to run for the safety of guards or rest is not only rude, but could be considered abuse.  If you want enchanters in general to keep this spell on their list, don't abuse it.<BR>
Other Illusions: You are going to end up travelling, that much is guaranteed.  Even if you could hunt and explore in the same region for your entire career, certain spells and items are only available in places far from home.  Sometimes merchants won't want to deal with you.  Even worse, sometimes guards will kill you on sight.  Using spells like Illusion: Dark Elf can help, but be warned that they don't last very long and may conk out when you cross zones.  You also have spells like Illusion: Skeleton for those late night gravediggers among us and Illusion: Tree for the nature lovers.<BR>
Invisibility/See Invisible: Whenever you travel alone your safest bet is to travel invisibly.  Receiving invisibility at level four allows us to travel to a lot of places others may fear to tread.  Have a party crossing dangerous territory?  Make your party members invisible, but first cast see invisible on them (level 8) so that you don't lose one another.<BR>
PLEASE NOTE THAT CERTAIN PEOPLE AND CREATURES THAT CAN SEE INVISIBLE CAN ALSO SEE THROUGH ILLUSIONS.  AMONG OTHERS, MUMMIES, MADMEN AND A LOT OF HIGH LEVEL MAGICAL MONSTERS WILL NOT BE FOOLED IF YOU DECIDE TO TURN YOURSELF INTO A CHAIR!<BR>
Enchant Spells:  A lot of people become enchanters for the opportunity to create their own magic items.  I don't have a whole lot to say about these spells right now except to note that the first enchant spell, Enchant: Silver, is only available in Neriak, the city of the dark elves.  Use extreme caution in retrieving it if you are not a Dark Elf yourself.<BR>
Other Utility Spells: Enchanters can allow people to breathe underwater, see at night, see through another's eyes, make items glow, get merchants to lower their prices (in theory), levitate, gate and a whole lot more.<BR>
The Future Spellbook: It is rumored that soon enchanters will be able to directly enchant existing weapons and items beyond Enchantment of Light.  Rumors also about an expansion of animation spells, to increase the variety of our pets, and expanding illusion spells, so that there will truly be nowhere an enchanter cannot infiltrate.<BR>

			<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</font></p>
					</p>
			</td>
